    <p>
        <lb n="1"/>svasti śrī-Turagana mane-magati<gap reason="undefined" unit="character" quantity="5"></gap>>vvajrā<gap reason="undefined" unit="character" quantity="2"></gap>
        <lb break="no" n="2"/>d ācāryyan Turagā nīnīyeḍeyol iḻdu kūḻaṁ gel<gap reason="undefined" unit="character" quantity="1"></gap><unclear>e</unclear>
        <lb break="no" n="3"/>ndoḍā mātan ollad<unclear>i</unclear>re sōlama<supplied reason="undefined">ṁ</supplied> kaṇḍātan <supplied reason="undefined">i</supplied>re sōlal āga
        <lb break="no" n="4"/>d endātaniṁ munna naḍadiṟidu paḍedaṁ yasamān ātaṁg<gap reason="undefined" unit="character" quantity="1"></gap>
        <lb break="no" n="5"/><gap reason="undefined" unit="character" quantity="1"></gap>ḷabbe laccakkan emboḷāke niṟisidaḷ ī kallaṁ
        
    </p>
</div>
     <div type="translation" source="bib:Barnett1921-1922_04">
      <p>Hail! <gap reason="undefined"></gap> the steward of the fortunate Turaga <gap reason="undefined"></gap> when the Ācārya of <gap reason="undefined"></gap> said:"O Turaga, stand in this place and conquer the base man", when he <supplied reason="explanation">Turaga</supplied> did not agree to that speech, and saw <supplied reason="subaudible">the prospect of</supplied> defeat, he said:"We must not be defeated", and advancing in front of him <supplied reason="explanation">Turaga</supplied> and stabbing <supplied reason="subaudible">the enemy</supplied>, he won fame. For him the mother <gap reason="undefined"></gap> she who is named Lacchakka, set up this stone.</p>
     </div>
